    <Entry>
      <ID>124</ID>
      <DefaultText>[OLD NODE; SHOULD NOT PLAY; DELETE AFTER REVISIONS ARE FINAL]

"The storied hero returns," the Memovira says. In person, she loses that shimmer effect, and you can see that the years and the stress of her position have not been kind. Her voice is tired, too. "Do you ever weary of the responsibility of power?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>125</ID>
      <DefaultText>"No. Why, do you?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>126</ID>
      <DefaultText>"On occasion, but it's my burden to bear."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>127</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Frequently, but it serves a purpose."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>128</ID>
      <DefaultText>"All that killing and stealing is finally getting to you, is it?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>129</ID>
      <DefaultText>Satsada's voice murmurs, "Tell me what you know of true responsibility, my lady. Let us speak of the screams you bade me induce."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>130</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Shut up, Matkina."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>131</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Quiet, Matkina. Please continue, Memovira."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>132</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Well said. We're just here for the Merecaster, and then we're gone. We don't intend to be friends."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>133</ID>
      <DefaultText>Her face hardens again, the moment of vulnerability gone. Her voice becomes brusque. "Very well. To business, then. You have retrieved the second Merecaster, I assume. I will need to examine it to ensure that this is the same one that was entrusted to my care."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>134</ID>
      <DefaultText>"This isn't your conversation, Satsada. Butt out."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>135</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Quiet, Satsada. The Memovira was speaking. Please continue."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>136</ID>
      <DefaultText>She doesn't say another word, but you *see* her psyche withdraw from Riastrad's nervous system. The look of anger and disapproval slowly vanishes from his face.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>137</ID>
      <DefaultText>Matkina glowers and withdraws into herself.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>138</ID>
      <DefaultText>She glances at your companion and considers her words carefully. "You know what it is to have others admire you, or to offer you adulation. You know how to manipulate people for power. So I ask you this: when does it become too much? When is it acceptable to walk away... or rather, to retire?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>139</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Quite right, Satsada. I do take responsibility for asking you to interrogate our enemies. Little did I know you'd be so... enthusiastic." She turns her attention to you. "Has she told you of her past employment with me yet? Ask her some time. It's an amusing tale." </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>140</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Oh it serves a purpose. Yet there are many who in live the Bloom who care nothing for my happiness. Nor should they. But if I leave, they suffer as the new ruler asserts her power here."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>141</ID>
      <DefaultText>"As you well know, Matkina, that's the easy part. It's having other people believe in you that's difficult. But why do I need to explain this to you? You're personally acquainted with this knowledge."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>142</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Walk away from power? Never. What's the point of gaining power if you don't use it?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>143</ID>
      <DefaultText>"It becomes too much only if you can't control it anymore. Until then, you should hold it tightly."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>144</ID>
      <DefaultText>"When your power no longer serves a purpose."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>145</ID>
      <DefaultText>"The point of power is that you don't have to listen to what other people want. You're talking about duty and responsibility - the power that others have over you."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>146</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I *have* used it. But now it grows tiresome. The pleasure has seeped from it."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>147</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Then retire. Find some other way to make yourself happy."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>148</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You're the ruler of the Bloom. What does your *pleasure* matter? You have a duty to your citizens."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>149</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Find a new pleasure. Novelties must come through the Bloom all the time."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>150</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Let me speak frankly, then." She considers her words carefully. "You know what it is to have others admire you, or to offer you adulation. You know how to manipulate people for power. So I ask you this: when does it become too much? When is it acceptable to walk away... or rather, to retire?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>151</ID>
      <DefaultText>"It's academic. I'm really just here for the Merecaster."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>152</ID>
      <DefaultText>"And if you feel your grip slipping?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>154</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Then you must make a choice. Let go altogether or fight to keep your position. There is no middle ground."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>155</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Then tighten it. Hold to it so it can't escape. Enough with the philosophy. Let's get to business."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>156</ID>
      <DefaultText>"What will they say of me? How will I be remembered?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>157</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Duty." She almost spits the word. "The duty I have to them is to keep them safe. I do this, and the thanks I get are knives in the dark and poisons in my cup."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>158</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Do the opinions of others truly matter that much to you?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>159</ID>
      <DefaultText>"As the one who walked away."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>160</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Do they remember the old Memoviras? Do you? Who reads the old histories?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>161</ID>
      <DefaultText>"As a coward, most likely."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>162</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Those who wish to learn from them. But you have a point. You may convince me yet."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>163</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Not a proud legacy." She considers. "But it might be a better story than being another one in the long line of Memoviras who have disappeared. You may convince me yet."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>164</ID>
      <DefaultText>"They do not. You have me half convinced." A small smile appears at the corner of her mouth.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>170</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You know Walks-without-fear? He was the old Memovira. The Bloom devoured his spirit, and it will do the same to you if you do not abandon the Bloom."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>171</ID>
      <DefaultText>"His spirit was broken before I ever took power. I said *convince me.*"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>172</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I spoke with the Observant Speck. She told me of the endless cycle of the Bloom's hunger, and what it does with its old rulers."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>173</ID>
      <DefaultText>She scoffs,"That old crone? She is a half-wit and a fanatic."

... but doubt lurks behind the mask of her face. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>174</ID>
      <DefaultText>"If you are truly the ruler of the Bloom, then you should also be the mistress of your own life. Control your destiny, and choose... rather than letting others act upon you. This is the truth of power."

